		<div class="entry"><span class="date">April 19, 2016</span><h5><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/04/19/should-therapists-write-about-patients/" title="Should Therapists Write About Patients?">Should Therapists Write About Patients?</a></h5><p><span class="excerpt-inner">Even when we disguise their identities, we risk betraying them.</span><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/04/19/should-therapists-write-about-patients/" class="more-link">Read&nbsp;more&#8230;</a></p></div><div class="entry"><span class="date">April 12, 2016</span><h5><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/04/12/grieving-my-patients-friend/" title="Grieving My Patient&#8217;s Friend">Grieving My Patient&#8217;s Friend</a></h5><p><span class="excerpt-inner">It isnât unusual for therapists to get emotionally attached to people we&#8217;ve never met. </span><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/2016/04/12/grieving-my-patients-friend/" class="more-link">Read&nbsp;more&#8230;</a></p></div><div class="entry"><p class="more"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/couch/">More From Couch &raquo;</a></p></div>		</div>
				<div class="tabContent">
